/**
 * "Kelly Email" AirApp demo — a real app-in-skill (an email review desk:
 * Hono server + zero-build vanilla frontend), not a synthetic illustration
 * like the rest of `demo-content.ts`. Ported from the `kelly-email` local
 * skill (external to this repo, lives at
 * `~/Documents/kelly-skills/skills/kelly-email` on the machine that
 * generated this file) — kept in its own file rather than inline in
 * `demo-content.ts` purely because of size (the bundled server alone is
 * ~160KB; every other demo in that file is a few KB of hand-written
 * illustrative code).
 *
 * The server side ships as ONE esbuild-bundled file
 * (`KELLY_EMAIL_SERVER_BUNDLE_JS`, placed at `lib/server.js` in the AirApp's
 * file tree — see below for why that exact path), not kelly-email's original
 * 24 separate `.ts` files. Reason: Nodepod's TypeScript stripper (its own
 * lightweight reimplementation, not tsc/swc/Node's own
 * `--experimental-strip-types`) fails to parse
 * `lib/data-provider/index.ts` with `SyntaxError: missing ) after argument
 * list` — confirmed as a genuine Nodepod limitation, not invalid syntax, by
 * parsing the exact same file with real Node's `--experimental-strip-types`
 * (succeeds cleanly). Bundling sidesteps this entirely and avoids relying on
 * unverified `.ts`-in-Nodepod support for the other 23 files.
 * `--packages=external` keeps real npm dependencies (hono, imapflow,
 * mailparser, nodemailer) as normal `node_modules` installs.
 *
 * The bundle is placed at `lib/server.js` — the SAME directory depth as the
 * original `lib/paths.ts` — because `lib/paths.ts`'s path constants
 * (SKILL_DIR, APP_DIR, CACHE_DIR, ...) are derived from
 * `dirname(fileURLToPath(import.meta.url))` at runtime. Bundling collapses
 * every module into whatever file location the bundle itself lands at, so
 * `import.meta.url` inside the bundled code now resolves relative to
 * wherever *that* file is — placing it anywhere other than `lib/`'s original
 * depth would silently miscompute APP_DIR (e.g. serving static files from a
 * doubled, nonexistent `app/app/` path). Placing it at the matching depth
 * keeps every derived path correct with zero code changes.
 *
 * kelly-email's own `launcher.ts` (PID file, port-scanning, daemonizing) is
 * intentionally excluded from the bundle entry point — Nodepod owns the
 * process lifecycle, so the plain `app/server/index.ts` entry (already used
 * by kelly-email's own `npm run serve`) is the correct one for an AirApp.
 * `lib/common.ts` and `scripts/*.ts` are excluded too — they back
 * kelly-email's CLI batch-review workflow, not the web UI this AirApp runs.
 *
 * Ships in local file mode by default (no env vars baked in) — a fresh Run
 * shows the "Set up Kelly Email" onboarding wizard, not a pre-connected
 * inbox; a real mailbox needs IMAP credentials entered through that flow,
 * never embedded in demo content. Heavier than the fast-baseline demos (48
 * npm packages to install, vs. zero for Pure HTML/Hono API/SQLite/Deal
 * Pipeline/Compliance Board), so it's in `ALL_AIRAPP_DEMOS` only — not the
 * `node-types.en.ts` fast baseline seed.
 *
 * Verified end-to-end: local Busabase instance, clicked Run, confirmed the
 * bundled server boots and the real onboarding UI renders in the preview
 * iframe — see `apps/busabase/content/changelog/20260716-kelly-email-airapp-port.md`.
 */

